questions.description:
Your orchestrator asks a Node service to stop by sending `SIGTERM`, then force-kills it with `SIGKILL` after a grace period.

```js
process.on('SIGTERM', () => {
  server.close(() => {   // stop taking new connections; fires once in-flight requests drain
    pool.end();          // release DB connections, flush logs, etc.
    process.exit(0);
  });
});
```

questions.explanation:
`server.close()` stops *accepting* new connections, but it does **not** terminate connections that are already open. With HTTP keep-alive, clients hold idle TCP connections open for reuse, so the "all connections closed" callback may not fire until each of those keep-alive sockets times out — making shutdown appear to hang.

Since **Node 18.2.0** you can drain them explicitly:

```js
process.on('SIGTERM', () => {
  server.close(() => process.exit(0));
  server.closeIdleConnections();   // drop idle keep-alive sockets right now
  // server.closeAllConnections();  // last-resort: also cut active ones
});
```

The distractors are myths: `server.close()` works on plain HTTP; a *ref'd* `setInterval` keeps the loop alive, but here the callback simply isn't firing, which points at connections, not timers; and `unref()` is unrelated to whether the close callback runs.

questions.description:
This handler runs on a single Node instance — no `cluster`, no `worker_threads`:

```js
app.get('/report', (req, res) => {
  let total = 0;
  for (let i = 0; i < 5e9; i++) total += i;  // several seconds of pure CPU
  res.json({ total });
});
```

Other requests — more `/report` calls and requests to unrelated routes alike — keep arriving at the **same instance**.
